{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491100"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:32:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:32:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"830"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/830"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.35,0.01,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"830"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83461"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/830"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"830"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68352"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5365"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11707"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1664"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1699"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28388"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83461"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old woman is being screened for breast cancer. Information is being sought from her family history to assess the likelihood of a BRCA mutation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following family histories would pose the greatest possibility of the presence of a BRCA mutation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mother with ovarian cancer diagnosed aged 60 and a sister with breast cancer diagnosed age 39","Mother with breast cancer diagnosed age 54 and sister with breast cancer diagnosed age 52","Mother with colon cancer diagnosed age 68 and sister with acute myeloid leukaemia diagnosed age 30","Father and brother with colon cancer diagnosed in their forties","Father with prostate cancer diagnosed age 70 and sister with gastric cancer diagnosed age 55"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of a \u003Cstrong\u003EBRCA mutation\u003C/strong\u003E is often suggested by a family history of breast and ovarian cancer, particularly when these cancers occur at a young age. In this scenario, the combination of a mother with ovarian cancer and a sister with early-onset breast cancer (diagnosed at age 39) is highly suggestive of a BRCA mutation. This is because BRCA mutations are strongly associated with both breast and ovarian cancers, and the early age of onset further increases suspicion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option with a \u003Cstrong\u003Emother and sister both having breast cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is concerning, but the later age of diagnosis (54 and 52) makes a BRCA mutation slightly less likely compared to the first option. While still possible, the risk is lower than when cancers occur at a younger age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA family history of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolon cancer\u003C/strong\u003E and acute myeloid leukaemia does not typically suggest a BRCA mutation. Colon cancer is more commonly associated with other genetic syndromes, such as Lynch syndrome, which does not have a strong link to breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolon cancer in male relatives\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicative of a BRCA mutation. While BRCA mutations can increase the risk of certain cancers in men, such as prostate cancer, colon cancer is not typically associated with BRCA mutations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough there is some evidence linking \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostate cancer\u003C/strong\u003E to BRCA mutations, the presence of gastric cancer in the family history does not support a BRCA mutation. Gastric cancer is not commonly associated with BRCA mutations, and the age of onset for prostate cancer in this scenario (age 70) is not particularly early.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["BRCA mutations significantly increase the risk of breast and ovarian cancer.","Family history of early-onset breast or ovarian cancer can indicate a higher likelihood of BRCA mutations."],"references":["Elezaby M, Lees B, Maturen K, Barroilhet L, Wisinski K, Schrager S et al. BRCAMutation Carriers: Breast and Ovarian Cancer Screening Guidelines and Imaging Considerations. Radiology. 2019;291(3):554-569.","Mehrgou A, Akouchekian M. The importance of BRCA1 and BRCA2 genes mutations in breast cancer development. Med J Islam Repub Iran. 2016 May 15;30:369. PMID: 27493913; PMCID: PMC4972064.","Royal Australian College of General Practitioners [Internet]. Melbourne Victoria: RACGP 2018. Guidelines for Preventative Activities in General Practice- early detection of breast cancer [updated 2018; cited 2021 Mar 02]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/guidelines-for-preventive-activities-in-general-pr/early-detection-of-cancers/breast-cancer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68352"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"830"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68352"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-04T18:54:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-04T18:56:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"830"}},"co